nkers' racial views and prejudices. Drawing deeply on a broad range of sources, Hudson reveals that the banks' experimental practices and projects in the Caribbean often led to embarrassing failure, and, eventually, literal erasure from the archives.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 22. Okt 2019) 0aBanks and bankingzCaribbean AreaxHistoryy20th century. 0aBanks and bankingzUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 0aBranch bankszCaribbean AreaxHistory. 0aCapitalismzUnited States. 0aCaribbean Area - Economic conditions - 20th century. 0aImperialismxEconomic aspectszUnited States. 0aRacismxEconomic aspectszUnited States. 4aCaribbean. 4aWall Street. 4abanking. 4acorruption. 4acrisis. 4adebt. 4aimperialism. 4ainternational finance. 4aregulation. 4asovereignty. 7aHISTORY / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press eBook Package 2016-2018z978311063537940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226459257423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780226459257.jpg  a978-3-11-063537-9  University of Chicago Press eBook Package 2016-2018c2016d2018  aGBV-deGruyter-alles